('Snatch from Hang (Knee)',
 'traps', array['glutes','hamstrings','shoulder','core'], array['traps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'Start with bar just above knees, hip-width stance. Hinge back until torso is roughly 45° — bar stays over mid-foot. Drive hips violently forward and up, shrug the traps, pull elbows high and wide. As bar reaches chest height, punch elbows under and catch bar overhead in squat. Stand to complete. Reset. This shortened pull teaches proper explosion mechanics without the full first pull complexity.',
 'Bar drifting away from body on pull; not completing the hip extension before pulling with the arms; catching with soft elbows; landing with feet too narrow; pressing out overhead instead of punching under.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Sweep the bar into your hips on the way up','Triple extension: ankle, knee, hip — all at once','Punch UNDER — not the bar up','Catch: soft landing, active shoulders overhead'],
 array['Full snatch from floor','Snatch balance','Hang snatch above knee for speed work'],
 array['Snatch deadlift to above knee','Power snatch high pull','Overhead squat for receiving position'],
 array['olympic_lifting','snatch','hang','technique','explosive','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','wrist_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Power Snatch',
 'traps', array['glutes','hamstrings','quads','shoulder'], array['traps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'Snatch caught in a partial squat (hips above parallel). Full approach from floor: setup wide grip, bar over mid-foot, hips above knees, chest up. First pull: maintain back angle while bar clears knees. Second pull: explosive extension, bar brushes hip crease. Third pull: pull under fast, catch bar overhead with slight knee bend. Useful for speed and technique work without requiring full overhead squat depth.',
 'Slow first pull losing position; not brushing the hips at full extension; catching too wide with soft lockout; feet landing too wide; not keeping the bar close throughout.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Bar path: straight up, not swinging out','Hip brush: the bar must touch you at the crease','Fast elbows: turn them out and under quickly','Catch: reach the floor through your heels'],
 array['Full squat snatch','Snatch from blocks at hip','Power snatch + overhead squat complex'],
 array['Hang power snatch from above knee','Snatch pull for technique','Snatch grip deadlift'],
 array['olympic_lifting','snatch','power_snatch','explosive','technique','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','lower_back_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Full Squat Snatch',
 'glutes', array['traps','hamstrings','quads','shoulder'], array['glutes','traps','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'The complete snatch. Wide grip (hands outside hips when arms at side). Setup: bar over mid-foot, wide stance, hips above knees, chest up, lats engaged. First pull slow and controlled to above knee maintaining torso angle. Second pull: explosive hip extension, bar brushes hip crease, full triple extension on toes. Third pull: aggressive pull under, punch elbows through, catch in full squat (below parallel) with bar locked out overhead. Stand with bar.',
 'Wide stance first pull causing bar to swing; not maintaining back position in first pull; early arm pull (arms should stay straight until after hip extension); catching with hips still above parallel; missing the turnaround from first to second pull.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Patience on the first pull: slow and controlled to the hip','Hips drive the bar, arms guide it','Pull yourself UNDER: the bar doesn''t go higher, you go lower','Catch: lock arms out before you hit the bottom'],
 array['Competition snatch heavy singles','1+1 snatch complex','Snatch EMOMs for volume'],
 array['Power snatch','Hang snatch below knee','Overhead squat work independently'],
 array['olympic_lifting','snatch','full_snatch','competitive_lifting','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','wrist_injury','lower_back'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 2, null, 180, true),

('Clean from Hang (Knee)',
 'glutes', array['traps','hamstrings','quads','biceps'], array['glutes','traps','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Hang clean from just above the knee. Shoulder-width grip, bar at knee, back flat, hips hinged. Drive hips through explosively, shrug traps, pull elbows up and around (not back), rotate wrists under, catch bar on front deltoids in front rack position with squat catch. Stand. Front rack: elbows high and forward, bar resting on clavicle and front delts, fingertips only on bar.',
 'Bar swinging away from body; catching in a stiff-legged position; elbows dropping in front rack; wrists not rotating through quickly; catching the bar on biceps rather than front rack.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Drive the hips: the explosion moves the bar, not your arms','Pull elbows HIGH and AROUND — not straight back','Front rack: elbows up like you''re pointing at the ceiling','Meet the bar: pull yourself under, don''t wait for it'],
 array['Full clean from floor','Power clean to front squat','Hang clean below knee'],
 array['Romanian deadlift for hip hinge pattern','Barbell front rack stretch','High pull for pull timing'],
 array['olympic_lifting','clean','hang_clean','technique','explosive','barbell'], array['wrist_injury','elbow_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Power Clean',
 'glutes', array['traps','hamstrings','quads'], array['glutes','traps','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Clean caught above parallel. From floor: hip-width stance, bar over mid-foot, double overhand grip, chest up, hips higher than knees. First pull: controlled, maintain back angle. Second pull: explosive triple extension, bar brushes thighs and hip crease. Catch: feet land slightly wider, hips above parallel, elbows punched through to high front rack. Stand. The power clean builds explosive hip extension and is a staple in athletic performance training.',
 'Bar not making contact at the hip crease; early arm bend ruining the pull; catching with arms instead of legs; hips not reaching full extension before pulling under; elbows in front rack below shoulder height.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['First pull: bar stays over mid-foot — not shifting forward','Hip contact: the brush generates the upward momentum','Punch through: elbows lead, wrists follow','Stomp: aggressive foot landing activates the catch'],
 array['Full squat clean','Clean + front squat complex','Power clean from blocks (hip height)'],
 array['Hang power clean from above knee','Power clean high pull','Romanian deadlift to clean pull progression'],
 array['olympic_lifting','clean','power_clean','athletic','explosive','barbell'], array['wrist_injury','lower_back_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Full Squat Clean',
 'glutes', array['traps','quads','hamstrings','core'], array['glutes','traps','quads'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'The complete clean. From floor with controlled first pull, violent second pull at hip crease, aggressive pull under into full front squat (below parallel), catch on front delts with elbows high. Drive out of the squat — push the floor away, maintain vertical torso. Bar stays on shoulders throughout stand. One of the most demanding full-body movements: requires pulling strength, speed under bar, front squat depth and strength.',
 'Soft catch causing collapse in the hole; elbows dropping in the squat; torso falling forward in the squat; not accelerating out of the hole; being slow in the transition from pull to squat.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Catch the squat: you meet the bar in the bottom','Elbows stay high throughout the squat','Drive from the heels: push the floor away','Fast turnover: the faster you get under, the heavier you can clean'],
 array['Competition clean heavy singles','Clean complex 1+1+1','Pause front squat for bottom position strength'],
 array['Power clean','Hang clean below knee full squat','Front squat max effort work'],
 array['olympic_lifting','clean','squat_clean','competitive_lifting','barbell'], array['knee_injury','wrist_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 2, null, 180, true),

('Clean and Jerk',
 'glutes', array['traps','quads','shoulder','triceps'], array['glutes','traps','quads'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'The king of Olympic lifts. Phase 1 (Clean): full squat clean as described. Reset front rack. Phase 2 (Jerk): dip and drive — feet hip-width, slight knee bend (not forward), violent leg drive, bar leaves shoulders, split underneath with front foot forward, back knee bent, catch bar locked overhead. Stand feet together. Two styles: split jerk (most common) or push jerk. Competition lift counts total on both movements.',
 'Dip too deep in jerk preparation losing speed; not completing drive before splitting feet; bar pressed forward rather than driven vertical; split position too narrow; pressing out instead of locking overhead.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Dip is shallow and fast — a piston, not a squat','Drive the bar straight: any forward angle is lost overhead','Lock it out BEFORE you step back together','Split: front shin vertical, back knee almost touching floor'],
 array['Competition clean and jerk maximum singles','Jerk from blocks for overhead development','Clean pull + clean + jerk complex'],
 array['Push press for jerk drive pattern','Split jerk footwork without bar','Power clean + push jerk'],
 array['olympic_lifting','clean_and_jerk','jerk','competitive_lifting','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','wrist_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 1, null, 180, true),

('Split Jerk from Rack',
 'shoulder', array['triceps','glutes','quads','core'], array['shoulder','triceps','glutes'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell','squat_rack'], 'advanced', false,
 'Jerk from rack eliminates the clean, allowing heavier jerk focus. Set bar on front rack. Stance: feet hip-width. Dip: controlled 5-6cm, knees track toes. Drive: violent leg extension, no pause between dip and drive. Split: front foot lands flat heel-to-toe, back foot on ball, back knee bends. Catch: arms locked, bar directly over hips, head through the window (head forward of the bar). Recover: front foot back, then back foot.',
 'Pause at the top of the dip destroying power; bar drifting forward off the shoulders; back knee not bending in split (reduces stability); rushing the recovery before balance is secured.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['Dip-drive is ONE movement: no pause','Bar rises: you split under it','Front foot: heel lands first, flat foot','Head through: look forward, bar over your centre of gravity'],
 array['Competition jerk from rack singles','Jerk behind neck','Push jerk variation for overhead stability'],
 array['Push press from rack','Jerk footwork drill with PVC','Overhead squat for overhead stability'],
 array['olympic_lifting','jerk','split_jerk','overhead','technique','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','lower_back'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Snatch Pull',
 'traps', array['hamstrings','glutes','lower_back'], array['traps','hamstrings','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Builds the pulling strength for the snatch without the catch. Snatch grip on bar. Initiate from floor with same back angle as snatch. First pull: controlled, bar rises to knee maintaining position. Second pull: explosive hip extension, full triple extension, shrug traps violently. Bar should rise to lower chest or higher on back extension. Allow bar to return to floor. Load heavier than snatch for strength development.',
 'Rounding back on first pull; early hip rise (the "stripper" pattern); not achieving full triple extension; not shrugging at the top; bending elbows in the pull.',
 'pulling_strength', array['Same position as your snatch — practice the pull you want','Hips and shoulders rise together off the floor','Shrug AFTER the legs are extended: sequence matters','Let the bar float at the top: don''t crash it down'],
 array['Snatch pull with pause at knee','Heavy snatch pull 110-120% of snatch','Snatch pull from deficit'],
 array['Snatch deadlift for position','Romanian deadlift for back strength','Power shrug'],
 array['olympic_lifting','snatch_pull','strength','technique_drill','barbell'], array['lower_back_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 4, null, 120, true),

('Clean Pull',
 'traps', array['hamstrings','glutes','lower_back'], array['traps','hamstrings','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Builds pulling strength for the clean without the catch. Clean grip. Same setup and first pull as clean. Second pull: explosive triple extension, violent hip extension, high shrug, elbows high as bar rises to lower chest height. Return controlled. Load: typically 100-110% of clean max for strength, or 80-90% for technique. 5-6 sets of 3 reps for strength development.',
 'Not maintaining clean-like positions; early arm bend; insufficient hip extension; pulling elbows back rather than up; not shrugging at the peak of extension.',
 'pulling_strength', array['Your clean pull is your clean: same position, just no catch','At full extension: stand tall, bar is floating, elbows high','Load heavy: this builds the engine that drives your clean','Shrug is the last thing in the sequence'],
 array['Clean pull from deficit','Heavy clean pull 110-120% max clean','Clean pull to above waist height'],
 array['Clean deadlift for back strength','Barbell shrug for trap development','Clean high pull'],
 array['olympic_lifting','clean_pull','strength','technique_drill','barbell'], array['lower_back_injury'],
