('Overhead Squat',
 'shoulder', array['core','glutes','quads','upper_back'], array['shoulder','core','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'The overhead squat tests and builds shoulder stability and hip mobility simultaneously. Snatch-width grip. Press bar overhead: arms locked, bar directly over spine and mid-foot. Squat to full depth (hip crease below knee) while maintaining vertical bar path and active shoulders. Active shoulder means pressing into the bar throughout — never passive. Core braced, thoracic spine extended throughout.',
 'Passive shoulders (worst mistake — causes bar to crash forward); forward lean causing bar drift; feet too narrow for depth; not actively pushing into bar throughout movement; knees collapsing inward.',
 'olympic_lifting', array['PRESS into the bar: active shoulders always','Vertical bar path: if it drifts forward, the squat fails','Grip it hard: a tight grip stabilizes the shoulder','You''re squatting under the bar, not holding it up'],
 array['Overhead squat with pause at bottom','Snatch balance from overhead squat position','Heavy overhead squat strength work'],
 array['PVC overhead squat for mobility','Dowel overhead squat','Snatch grip Romanian deadlift for mobility'],
 array['olympic_lifting','overhead_squat','shoulder_stability','mobility','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','thoracic_kyphosis_severe'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 120, true),

('Hang Clean High Pull',
 'traps', array['glutes','hamstrings','shoulder'], array['traps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Teaching drill for the second pull of the clean. Bar at hip crease or above knee. Violent hip extension, shrug, pull elbows as high as possible (elbows above shoulders). Bar rises to chin height or higher. The high pull teaches the arm action of the clean without the complexity of catching. Key: elbows must lead — not the hands.',
 'Pulling with biceps rather than elbows leading; not achieving full hip extension before pulling; bar swinging away from body; shrugging without hip extension (partial movement).',
 'technique_drill', array['Elbows lead: they go UP and OUT, not back','Hips first, then pull: don''t skip the extension','Bar stays close: it should brush your shirt on the way up','Peak: elbows above shoulders — that''s your catch height'],
 array['Full hang clean from same position','Power snatch with pause at hip','Clean pull from floor with high pull finish'],
 array['Barbell shrug for trap awareness','Upright row with wide grip','Romanian deadlift for hip hinge'],
 array['olympic_lifting','high_pull','clean','technique_drill','explosive','barbell'], array['elbow_injury','shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 90, true),

('Muscle Snatch',
 'shoulder', array['traps','triceps','upper_back'], array['shoulder','traps','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'advanced', false,
 'The muscle snatch pulls the bar overhead without re-bending the knees (no dip under the bar). Snatch grip, begin from hang or floor. Explosive pull as in snatch but instead of pulling under, continue pulling the bar overhead maintaining arm contact all the way. Turn over into a press-out as bar reaches forehead height, lock out overhead. Lighter than snatch — excellent for shoulder strength and turnover speed.',
 'Using too much weight (defeats the technique purpose); bending elbows and pressing out instead of continuous pull; bar losing contact with body during the pull; not maintaining lockout at top.',
 'technique_drill', array['Keep the bar moving: it never stops on its way up','Your elbows turn out at the top — like an external rotation','This is a strength drill: chase shoulder stability not weight','Lockout: punch up, not forward'],
 array['Muscle snatch + overhead squat complex','Muscle snatch for shoulder warm-up high frequency','Transition from muscle snatch to power snatch'],
 array['PVC muscle snatch technique practice','Press in snatch position','Snatch grip Romanian deadlift'],
 array['olympic_lifting','muscle_snatch','shoulder','technique_drill','barbell'], array['shoulder_instability','rotator_cuff_tear'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 90, true),

('Snatch Balance',
 'shoulder', array['glutes','quads','core'], array['shoulder','glutes','quads'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['barbell'], 'advanced', false,
 'From behind the neck, bar on traps, snatch grip. Simultaneously: dip shallow (2-3cm), drive bar up, split feet to squat width, and drop under bar into full overhead squat position. This trains the speed of getting under the bar and the aggressiveness of the turnover. One of the hardest confidence builders for the snatch — develops the instinct to drop under the bar.',
 'Pressing the bar up rather than driving and dropping; feet not landing in squat position; not catching in the bottom (only partial squat); being passive instead of driving aggressively.',
 'technique_drill', array['Drive it up, then drop UNDER: not just holding it','Your feet land at the same time your arms lock out','Aggressive: there is no gentle snatch balance','Bottom position: active shoulders, heels down, elbows locked'],
 array['Snatch balance from squat position (drop snatch)','Heavy snatch balance loading','Snatch balance into walk-out'],
 array['PVC overhead squat for receiving position','Press behind neck for overhead strength','Snatch grip push press'],
