('Pause Squat',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','core'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Low bar or high bar squat with a 2-3 second pause at the bottom. Descend to full depth, hold position completely still — no bouncing, no tension loss — for the count. Then drive up explosively. The pause eliminates the stretch-shortening cycle, forcing maximum muscular strength from the bottom. Builds raw strength out of the hole and eliminates form breakdown at the bottom.',
 'Collapsing during pause (knees diving in, torso falling forward); counting too fast; bouncing off the bottom instead of pausing; reducing the load too much (should be ~80-85% of regular back squat).',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Pause: completely still — if you move, it''s not a pause','Drive the knees out during the pause','Breathe and brace again before driving out','Explosion after the pause: don''t ease out of the hole'],
 array['Pause squat + regular squat complex','3-second pause squat at near maximal load','Pause front squat for Olympic lifting carryover'],
 array['Box squat to box (breaks stretch-shortening cycle)','Goblet squat pause for technique','Pause squat with empty bar'],
 array['powerlifting','pause_squat','squat','strength','technique','barbell'], array['knee_injury','hip_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 4, null, 180, true),

('Box Squat',
 'glutes', array['quads','hamstrings','hip_flexors'], array['glutes','quads','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','plyo_box'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Squat to a box (set at parallel or below). Sit back aggressively — more horizontal shin angle than free squat. Hips sit on the box briefly (2 seconds) — do not bounce. Maintain braced spine. Then drive up explosively, hips first. Box squat develops posterior chain dominance and teaches the sit-back pattern critical for raw powerlifting. Box height: parallel for strength, slightly above for technique.',
 'Bouncing off the box; leaning too far forward; not maintaining tension during the sit; box too high (not reaching parallel); narrow stance reducing posterior chain engagement.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Sit BACK: your shins should be close to vertical','Tension: you sit on the box, you don''t collapse onto it','Drive hips: push them back and up from the box','Wide stance: more glute activation'],
 array['Box squat against bands or chains','Sub-parallel box squat for depth','Box squat max effort work (Westside method)'],
 array['Goblet squat to box for technique','Box squat with light bar','Leg press to similar depth'],
 array['powerlifting','box_squat','posterior_chain','strength','barbell'], array['knee_injury','hip_replacement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 180, true),

('Tempo Bench Press (3-1-1)',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder','lats'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','bench'], 'intermediate', true,
 '3-second lowering, 1-second pause on chest, 1-second press. Reduces weight from regular bench but eliminates bounce and forces full pectoral activation through the full range. The pause eliminates elastic recoil. Develops the strength in the toughest part of the bench press — the bottom position. Use 70-75% of regular bench press 1RM.',
 'Letting the bar sink into chest with no muscle activity during the pause; losing tension in the lats on the way down; the bar drifts toward the face instead of lower chest; too much weight causing breakdown.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Lower with control: 3 full seconds','Pause: bar on chest, everything engaged, nothing moving','Press: drive bar in a slight arc toward the face','Lats engaged throughout: they are your foundation'],
 array['Pause bench press at various positions','Tempo bench with bands','Competition bench press with pause on command'],
 array['Normal bench press technique focus','Dumbbell bench press paused','Floor press for shorter range of motion'],
 array['powerlifting','bench_press','tempo','pause','strength','technique'], array['shoulder_impingement','pec_tear'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 120, true),

('Pin Press',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','power_rack'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Bench press from safety pins set at various heights. Commonly used to target sticking points. Setup bar on pins at the bottom of your sticking point (usually 2-4cm off the chest). Lie under bar. Brace. Drive bar off the pins from a dead stop — no momentum, no stretch reflex. The bar starts at the pins, so you train the exact position where you fail. Also useful: pin just below lockout to train the top of the press.',
 'Bouncing bar off pins (defeats the purpose — dead stop only); wrong pin height (not at actual sticking point); insufficient lat engagement at the start; breathing and bracing after the movement begins.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Dead stop: no help from the bounce','Find your sticking point: that''s your pin height','Brace before you press — not during','Start aggressive: it requires maximum intent from zero'],
 array['Pin press at sticking point with bands','Max effort pin press singles','Pin press complex: bottom pin to full press'],
 array['Regular bench press with pause on chest','Floor press','Board press for upper range sticking point'],
 array['powerlifting','pin_press','bench','sticking_point','strength','rack'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 180, true),

('Slingshot Bench Press',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder','lats'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','bench','slingshot'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Bench press with a Slingshot (reactive shoulder sleeve) provides assistance at the bottom and resistance at the top. Allows 10-20% more load than regular bench while protecting shoulder at bottom position. Excellent for overloading the top range and acclimating to heavier loads. Best used after base bench work. Full technique identical to regular bench — the Slingshot enhances but should not substitute proper mechanics.',
 'Relying on the slingshot to compensate for poor technique; using too much weight and losing arch/lat engagement; not using it as a tool within a structured program.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Treat it like regular bench: same setup, same press','The sling gives you bottom support: use it to push more weight','Overload: go heavier than your working sets here','Technique first: the slingshot amplifies what you bring'],
 array['Slingshot max effort heavy singles','Slingshot for volume accumulation at high load','Competition bench press development'],
 array['Regular bench press technique','Close grip bench for tricep strengthening','Larsen press for upper body strength'],
 array['powerlifting','slingshot','bench_press','overload','strength'], array['shoulder_impingement','pec_tear_recent'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 5, null, 180, true),

('Deadlift Deficit Pull',
 'glutes', array['hamstrings','lower_back','traps'], array['glutes','hamstrings','lower_back'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','plates'], 'advanced', true,
 'Deadlift standing on a 2-5cm deficit (plates or small platform). Increases the range of motion, making the lift harder from the floor. Forces better starting position mechanics — greater hip bend, more leg involvement, stronger initial drive. Use 85-90% of regular deadlift max. Excellent for addressing weakness off the floor. Conventional or sumo stance as per your competition style.',
 'Too large a deficit making technique collapse (>5cm); rounding lower back due to increased range; using the same weight as regular deadlift (too heavy for the added range); losing lat engagement throughout.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Greater range: start lower and drive harder','More leg in it: your quads do more work off the deficit','Same back position: no more rounding just because it''s harder','Deficit builds your floor strength: specific to the hardest part'],
 array['Deadlift from deficit with bands (accommodating resistance)','Single-leg deadlift Romanian variant','Pause deadlift from deficit'],
 array['Regular deadlift','Rack pull from knee height','Romanian deadlift for posterior chain'],
 array['powerlifting','deficit_deadlift','deadlift','strength','barbell'], array['lower_back_injury','disc_herniation'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 4, null, 180, true),

('Deadlift Rack Pull',
 'traps', array['glutes','hamstrings','lower_back'], array['traps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','power_rack'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Deadlift starting from pins set at knee height or above. Reduces range of motion allowing heavier loads. Develops upper back, trap, and lockout strength. Also used for grip training with heavier-than-max weights. Set pins at desired height. Pull and lock out. Primary weakness targeted: above the knee to lockout. Common heights: mid-shin, below knee, at knee, above knee.',
 'Bar rolling excessively (rack pulls are harder on grip — may use straps after initial grip sets); hyperextending lower back at lockout; lower back rounding at start position.',
 'powerlifting_accessory', array['Lockout: hips through, shoulders back, squeeze glutes','Grip it hard: your hands must keep up with the load','Same back position as your pull from the floor','Drive through the heels even though the range is shorter'],
 array['Rack pull with bands for lockout','Above-knee rack pull at near-max loads','Rack pull to develop specific lockout weakness'],
 array['Regular deadlift','Hip hinge pattern practice','Trap bar deadlift for reduced spinal load'],
