 'Bench press with legs raised (feet on the bench end or straight up). Eliminates leg drive and reduces lower back arch, placing greater demand on the upper body. Forces the lats and core to provide all stability. Builds raw upper body pressing strength. Also effective for identifying leg drive reliance. Use 80-90% of competition bench.',
 'Lower back completely flat (some natural arch is fine — removing all arch is not the goal); bar drifting toward face; losing lat tightness without the leg drive anchor; treating as a core exercise rather than a pressing exercise.',
