('Tabata Protocol (20s On / 10s Off)',
 'cardiovascular', array['quads','core','shoulder'], array['cardiovascular','quads','core'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['bodyweight','kettlebell','bike'], 'intermediate', true,
 'True Tabata protocol: 8 rounds of 20 seconds maximum effort / 10 seconds complete rest. Total: 4 minutes. Original research (Tabata, 1996) used cycle ergometer. Any exercise works: air squats, burpees, push-ups, bike sprints. The critical factor: 20 seconds must be ALL-OUT effort. If you''re not completely exhausted by round 6-8, you''re not working hard enough. Can be chained: 2-4 Tabata blocks with 2-min rest between.',
 'Not going hard enough (Tabata only works with maximal effort); using too complex an exercise that limits intensity; using the rest as extra time rather than a hard reset; doing Tabata daily (requires 48h recovery).',
 'HIIT', array['20 seconds: as many reps as humanly possible','10 seconds: breathe, brace, restart','Rounds 5-8 are where adaptation happens: go hardest here','This should feel like you might die: that''s the point'],
 array['Tabata with heavier implement (kettlebell swings)','Double Tabata (2 exercises alternating)','Sport-specific movement Tabata'],
 array['Moderate-intensity intervals 30s on / 30s off','Zone 4 sustained effort without maximal bursts','Simple AMRAP without timed rest'],
 array['HIIT','tabata','metabolic','anaerobic','conditioning','intervals'], array['cardiovascular_condition','severe_hypertension'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 8, null, 20, 10, true),

('EMOM (Every Minute on the Minute)',
 'cardiovascular', array['core','shoulder','quads'], array['cardiovascular','core','shoulder'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['barbell','kettlebell','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Perform a set number of reps at the top of every minute. Remaining time in the minute is rest. Example: 10x power cleans at 60% EMOM 10 minutes. The density increases as fatigue accumulates (less rest). Scales for every fitness level. Best for: barbell strength-endurance, kettlebell work, gymnastics skills. Prescribe reps at ~40-60% of your max set capacity for the movement.',
 'Starting too heavy (exhausted by minute 4); reps taking too long reducing rest; not having clock visible; choosing too complex a movement that slows significantly under fatigue.',
 'conditioning', array['Choose a weight you could do 15+ reps of, not your max','Consistent pace: rep 1 and rep 10 should look identical','Rest is earned: efficient movement = more rest','Use a loud clock or beeper — don''t count seconds'],
 array['EMOM with increasing weight each 5 minutes','Alternating EMOM: two movements A/B','Heavy EMOM with 1-2 reps at 85-90%'],
 array['AMRAP at own pace without time per set','Simple 3 sets of 10 without time structure','Interval training with fixed rest periods'],
 array['HIIT','EMOM','conditioning','barbell','metabolic','programming'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 10, null, null, null, true),

('AMRAP Circuit (As Many Rounds as Possible)',
 'cardiovascular', array['core','quads','shoulder'], array['cardiovascular','core','shoulder'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['bodyweight','barbell','dumbbells'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Complete as many rounds of a movement circuit as possible in a set time (10-20 minutes). Example: 5 pull-ups, 10 push-ups, 15 air squats. Move continuously, transition between exercises quickly. Score: total rounds + partial reps completed. Scales to any fitness level by adjusting reps and movements. The time pressure builds mental and physical capacity simultaneously.',
 'Starting too fast burning out in first 5 minutes; stopping between exercises rather than transitioning; comparing to others rather than pacing own capacity; using excessive load reducing total work done.',
 'conditioning', array['Sustainable pace: you should be moving at minute 15 as at minute 1','Transitions are seconds: no standing between movements','Score yourself: track and beat your score next session','The last 2 minutes: push harder — you''re almost done'],
 array['Loaded AMRAP with barbell movements','Ascending AMRAP: add 1 rep each round','Partner AMRAP (you go / I go format)'],
 array['Timed circuit with fixed rest between rounds','Simple 3-exercise circuit for beginners','2-round max effort circuit'],
 array['HIIT','AMRAP','circuit','metabolic','conditioning','CrossFit'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, null, null, true),

('Assault Bike Sprint Intervals',
 'cardiovascular', array['quads','shoulder','glutes'], array['cardiovascular','quads','shoulder'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['assault_bike'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Assault bike (air bike) intervals. The fan resistance means harder effort = more resistance. Sprint protocols: (1) 10x30s all-out with 90s rest. (2) Tabata: 8x20s/10s. (3) 5x1-minute all-out with 2 minutes rest. Track watts or calories. The assault bike is merciless — using both arms and legs, it challenges cardiovascular capacity unlike any single-limb machine. Target: produce more calories or higher watts each set.',
 'Not using arms (reduces total output significantly); choosing insufficient resistance (increase RPM or effort for max output); starting too hard and fading; poor posture causing inefficient power transfer.',
 'conditioning', array['Arms AND legs: this is a full-body push','Sprint from the first pedal stroke: no gradual build','Track your calories: they give you honest feedback','3-2-1-go: do not ease into sprints'],
 array['Assault bike marathon (60 min steady)','Assault bike death by calories','Partner assault bike relay race'],
 array['Moderate pace bike with no sprints','Steady 5-minute efforts at 60-70% max','Recovery ride on assault bike easy pace'],
 array['HIIT','assault_bike','cardiovascular','sprint','conditioning','calorie_burn'], array['shoulder_injury','cardiovascular_condition'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 10, null, 30, 90, true),

('Rowing Machine HIIT',
 'cardiovascular', array['lats','glutes','quads','core'], array['cardiovascular','lats','glutes'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['rowing_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 '500m row sprints as the standard HIIT unit. 8x500m at maximum effort (aim for 1:45-2:00/500m depending on fitness). Rest: equal time to your row (if 1:55, rest 1:55). Track splits: consistency is the marker of pacing competence. Drive sequence: legs push first, body leans back, then arms pull (3 phases). On the recovery: arms extend first, body leans forward, then knees bend.',
 'Pulling with arms first (reduces power significantly); rounding the back throughout; inadequate drive off the footplate; seat sliding too far forward at catch; not maintaining stroke rate consistency.',
 'conditioning', array['Legs push: 60% of the power comes from your legs','Drive sequence: legs-body-arms; recover arms-body-legs','Sit tall: back nearly vertical during the pull','Split time is truth: check it and chase it'],
 array['2000m row time trial','Rowing intervals at stroke rate targets','10-minute max calories row challenge'],
 array['Easy 5-minute row warm-up moderate pace','Technique focus row at low stroke rate (18 spm)','Short 250m efforts for introduction'],
 array['HIIT','rowing','cardiovascular','conditioning','metabolic','full_body'], array['lower_back_injury','knee_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 8, null, null, null, true),

('Ski Erg Intervals',
 'lats', array['shoulder','core','triceps'], array['lats','shoulder','core'],
 'cardio', 'cardio', array['ski_erg'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Ski erg (SkiErg) upper-body focused conditioning. Drive both arms down and back simultaneously while hinging at the hips. Pull: hands from overhead to below hips in a powerful arc. Stand slightly and reset for next rep. Sprint protocol: 10x30s all-out / 30s rest. Pacing session: 1000m at sustainable pace. Targets: lat, tricep, core, and cardiovascular system. Particularly effective for upper-body dominant conditioning.',
 'Using only arms without the hip hinge (reduces power); chopping short rather than full arm extension overhead; bent-over position preventing proper hip hinge; too much back involvement relative to lat focus.',
 'conditioning', array['Reach long overhead before each pull','Drive from the hips: it''s a full-body movement','Arms finish below the hips: complete the range','Standing tall between pulls: reset position'],
 array['Ski erg 4-minute max distance','Double ski erg arms with squat combination','Weighted vest ski erg for added demand'],
 array['Easy pace ski erg for warm-up','Seated banded row for similar pull pattern','Lat pulldown for overhead pull strength'],
 array['HIIT','ski_erg','upper_body','cardiovascular','conditioning','full_body'], array['shoulder_injury','rotator_cuff_tear'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 10, null, 30, 30, true),

('Devil Press',
 'glutes', array['shoulder','core','hamstrings'], array['glutes','shoulder','core'],
 'cardio', 'explosive', array['dumbbells'], 'advanced', true,
 'Dumbbell burpee to alternating dumbbell snatch. Hold dumbbells, kick feet back to push-up position, perform push-up (optional), jump feet forward, explosively stand and hinge, then snatch both dumbbells overhead in a single movement (like a dumbbell clean and press driven from the hip). Lower dumbbells and repeat. Full body conditioning movement used heavily in CrossFit and HYROX training.',
 'Using the arms to lift rather than the hip drive; pressing the dumbbells overhead instead of snatching; collapsing in the burpee phase; landing with soft knees after the overhead.',
 'conditioning', array['Hip drive: the dumbbells should feel weightless at the top','Straight arms at lockout: fully extended overhead','Burpee first, snatch second: two distinct phases','Ground your feet before the drive: plant, then explode'],
