('Kettlebell Long Cycle (Clean and Jerk)',
 'glutes', array['shoulder','traps','core'], array['glutes','shoulder','traps'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['kettlebell'], 'advanced', false,
 'The king of kettlebell sport: clean and jerk with one or two kettlebells. Swing bell(s) between legs, clean to rack position (bell rests on forearm, wrist straight, elbow on hip), pause briefly, then jerk overhead (dip, drive, split or squat under). Lower to rack, then swing back between legs. Competition: max reps in 10 minutes. The rack position efficiency determines sustainability — the bell should rest, not be held.',
 'Active rack (carrying the bell with the arm rather than resting it on the forearm); too narrow a dip on the jerk; not using the hip drive efficiently; trying to muscle press instead of jerk; poor breathing (exhale on each cycle).',
 'kettlebell_sport', array['Rack position: the bell rests — you rest in it','Jerk: two-phase dip-drive — not a press','Breathe on the swing-back: exhale and inhale in the back-swing','Efficiency is the sport: relax between reps'],
 array['Long cycle competition 10 min test','Double kettlebell long cycle','Long cycle training sets 3-5 min'],
 array['Kettlebell clean only for rack practice','Push press with bell for overhead mechanics','Single bell jerk without clean'],
