('Kettlebell Bottoms-Up Press',
 'shoulder', array['rotator_cuff','forearm','core'], array['shoulder','rotator_cuff','forearm'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['kettlebell'], 'advanced', false,
 'Hold kettlebell upside down (bell up, handle pointing to floor). Press from shoulder height to full overhead extension while maintaining the bell balanced upside-down. The instability of the inverted bell forces maximum rotator cuff activation and wrist stability. An excellent diagnostic: if you can bottoms-up press a bell, your shoulder and wrist stability are strong. Start 30-40% lighter than your regular press.',
 'Wrist buckling under the bell; insufficient grip pressure (grip hard = more stability); bell drifting forward out of stack; too much weight making control impossible.',
 'shoulder_stability', array['Grip white-knuckle tight: grip stabilises the whole chain','Stack: wrist over elbow over shoulder','Press slow: control is the exercise','The bell wobbles? Grip harder and slow down'],
 array['Bottoms-up press walking (carry)','Bottoms-up half-kneeling press for core engagement','Bottoms-up Turkish get-up'],
 array['Regular KB press for shoulder strength base','External rotation exercises for rotator cuff','Wrist stability exercises'],
 array['kettlebell','bottoms_up','shoulder_stability','rotator_cuff','advanced','diagnostic'], array['wrist_injury','shoulder_instability'],
