('Kettlebell Renegade Row',
 'lats', array['core','shoulder','triceps'], array['lats','core','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['kettlebell'], 'advanced', false,
 'Push-up position with hands on two kettlebells (parallel handles). Stabilise in plank. Row one kettlebell to hip while the other arm stabilises. Return. Row the other side. The anti-rotation demand of the planted arm is the core challenge. The flat-bottomed kettlebell provides a stable base for the push-up element. Maintain a rigid plank throughout — no hip rotation.',
 'Hip rotation during the row (reduces anti-rotation demand); using a bell that''s too light eliminating the anti-rotation challenge; performing a push-up with each row (optional but changes the movement pattern); not keeping elbow close to body during row.',
 'functional_strength', array['No hip rotation: your hips should be level throughout','Elbow close: row to hip, not to shoulder','Plank position: engaged core, neutral spine','Anti-rotation is the point: the harder it is to stay still, the better'],
 array['Renegade row with push-up','Renegade row with heavier bell','Renegade row to snatch combination'],
 array['Dumbbell row from bench','Regular push-up position plank hold','TRX row for anti-rotation training'],
