('Ring Muscle-Up',
 'chest', array['lats','triceps','shoulder','core'], array['chest','lats','triceps'],
 'strength', 'explosive', array['gymnastic_rings'], 'advanced', true,
 'Muscle-up on gymnastic rings. Rings allow more natural wrist movement, making the transition slightly more accessible for wrist mobility, but harder for stability. False grip setup: wrist rests on the ring, allowing the transition. Pull explosively, lever over rings, push to straight-arm support in ring dip top position. Rings move — this instability adds significant shoulder and core demand. The ring muscle-up is a benchmark of calisthenics training.',
 'Not using false grip (makes the transition impossible for beginners); rings set too high or too low; not maintaining control in the top position; kipping excessively masking strength deficit.',
 'gymnastics_strength', array['False grip: the ring sits in the crook of your wrist','Pull fast and high: the higher the pull, the easier the transition','Turn your palms forward at the top (rings rotate naturally)','Straight arm support: stand on your hands above the rings'],
 array['Weighted ring muscle-up','Ring muscle-up with slow transition','Strict ring muscle-up (no kip)'],
 array['False grip hang and pull practice','Ring pull-up to chest height','Jumping ring muscle-up with band assist'],
 array['calisthenics','ring_muscle_up','rings','gymnastics','advanced','strength'], array['shoulder_instability','wrist_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 5, 3, null, 180, true),

('Front Lever',
 'lats', array['core','shoulder','biceps'], array['lats','core','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'isometric', array['pull_up_bar','gymnastic_rings'], 'advanced', false,
 'Static hold: body horizontal facing up, arms straight overhead, gripping a bar or rings. Entire body parallel to the ground. Hold the tuck position first (knees to chest), progress to single-leg (one leg extended, one tucked), then advanced tuck, then full front lever. Full front lever: body horizontal, legs together, toes pointed, arms straight overhead. 3-5 sets of 3-10 second holds.',
 'Pulling with bent arms rather than straight arms (the difficulty must come from lat and core engagement); not maintaining a hollow body position; rushing from tuck to full before adequate strength is developed; inconsistent measurement of hold time.',
 'gymnastics_strength', array['Hollow body: the same hollow position as your planks','Lat engagement: think about pulling the bar to your hips','Arms straight: if they bend, you''re not at the right progression','Progression patience: spend 3-4 weeks at each stage'],
 array['Full front lever holds 10+ seconds','Front lever pull-up (advanced compound)','Front lever to back lever sequence'],
 array['Tuck front lever hold','Assisted front lever with band support','Inverted row with feet elevated'],
