('Handstand (Against Wall)',
 'shoulder', array['core','triceps','traps'], array['shoulder','core','triceps'],
 'strength', 'isometric', array['wall','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Inverted hold with wall support. Kick up to wall, hands shoulder-width, arms straight. Balance with fingertips pressing to maintain position. Body line: straight from hands to heels — not an arch or a pike. Hold for time. The wall handstand is the foundation for freestanding handstand balancing. Wall-facing (chest to wall): tests truly straight body line. Wall-backing (chest away from wall): easier to kick into.',
 'Arching the back (banana handstand); hands too wide; not pressing through the fingertips for balance; looking at the floor instead of between hands; kicking up too hard and hitting the wall forcefully.',
 'gymnastics_strength', array['Straight line: heels, hips, shoulders, hands — all stacked','Press fingertips: balance is controlled here, not the shoulders','Look between your hands: not at the floor','Body tight: squeeze everything'],
 array['Freestanding handstand','Handstand push-up','Handstand walk'],
 array['Downward dog for shoulder alignment','Pike push-up for shoulder strength','Elevated pike shoulder press'],
