('Ring Dip',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder','core'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['gymnastic_rings'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Dip on gymnastic rings. Start in top position: arms locked, rings turned out (thumbs forward). Lower body by bending elbows, elbows track at approximately 45°, chest slightly forward. Lower until shoulders are at ring height or below. Press back to lockout, turning rings out again at the top. The ring dip is significantly harder than bar dips due to the instability — rings move in three dimensions requiring constant stabilisation.',
 'Not turning rings out at the top (reduces shoulder stability); going too deep before adequate strength; shaky rings indicating insufficient ring dip strength (regress to box dips or bar dips); allowing rings to drift wide.',
 'chest_tricep_strength', array['Turn out at top: thumbs point outward in the lockout','Elbow track: not straight back, not straight out — 45°','Control the descent: rings wobble = too fast','Rings stay close to your body throughout'],
